legislators must enforce their own provisions, an arrangement that is seriously compromised by their unwillingness to abide by rules that demand short-term sacrifices for the sake of long-term gain. Convinced that budget rules enacted through such a flawed legislative process are unlikely to work, Primo ultimately calls for a careful debate over the advantages and drawbacks of a constitutional convention initiated by the states—a radical step that would bypass Congress to create a path toward change. Rules and Restraint will be required reading for anyone interested in institutional design, legislatures, and policymaking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agovernment spending, budget, politics, political science, economics, tax revenue, taxation, loopholes, social programs, legislation, law, congress, nonfiction, history, constitutional convention, policymaking, legislatures, institutional design, finance, enforcement, federal, state, local, rules, mandate, regulation, pork barrel.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226682617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226682617/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles